Project Summary
This project is a Microservices-based DevOps system

## Architecture
1. Docker (Containerization) → I used Docker to containerize each microservice so the application runs consistently across environments.
2. Kubernetes (Container Orchestration) → I used Kubernetes to deploy and manage containers, ensuring automatic restarts and scalability.
3. AWS EC2 (Cloud Deployment) → I deployed the application on AWS EC2 to make it publicly accessible over the internet.
4. Prometheus (Monitoring) → I used Prometheus to collect metrics like request count and service performance.
5. Grafana (Visualization) → I used Grafana to visualize Prometheus metrics through dashboards.
6. Redis (Caching) → I used Redis to cache product data and reduce database load.
7. Terraform (Infrastructure as Code) → I used Terraform to provision AWS resources like EC2 and security groups automatically.
8. AWS S3(Storage)
9. DockerHub (Container Registry) → I pushed Docker images to DockerHub for easy access and deployment in Kubernetes.
10. Kubernetes Autoscaling (HPA) → I configured HPA to automatically scale pods based on CPU usage.
11. Elastic IP (Static Public Access) → I used Elastic IP to provide a fixed public IP for accessing my application.
12. Swagger (API Documentation) → I used Swagger to document and test API endpoints interactively.
13. GitHub Actions (CI/CD) → I used GitHub Actions to automate build and deployment to EC2 on every code push.

